{
  "answer": "**The work is *San Hyan Mahajnana* (work slug: `unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531`), Chapter 1.**[^1]\n\nThis chapter uses the metaphor of the *puruṣa* (the Self or pure consciousness) trapped like a *nāga* (serpent) in the \"terrible ocean of *saṃsāra*\"—the worldly cycle of suffering, akin to terrifying waters.[^2] The sacred syllable *oṃkāra* is identified as *Garuḍa*, the mythical bird that lifts the serpent out, bringing the *puruṣa* to *śivapada* (Shiva's abode).[^3]\n\n**The verse naming *puruṣa* as *nāga* and *oṃkāra* as *Garuḍa*:**  \n*In the terrible ocean of saṃsāra, puruṣa is situated like a nāga. Knowing oṃkāra to be Garuḍa [...] for the effort [...] // 64*[^4]\n\n**The prose line stating that *oṃkāra* brings the Self to *śivapada*:**  \n\"The holy *oṃkāra* is named Garuḍa. He is the one who brings the revered *puruṣa* to *śivapada*.\"[^5]\n\n[^1]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1, [/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/].\n[^2]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1, [/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-7b2370].\n[^3]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1, [/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-d9dbdf].\n[^4]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1, [/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-7b2370].\n[^5]: *San Hyan Mahajnana*, Chapter 1, [/works/unknown-san-hyan-mahajnana-11c531/01/translation/#p-d9dbdf].",
